'''Louise Doris Adams''' (died 1966) was a British [[mathematics education|mathematics educator]] and [[Ofsted#Inspectors|school inspector]] (HMI) who wrote the 1953 book ''A Background to Primary School Mathematics'' (Oxford University Press){{r|cook|edres}} and became president of the [[Mathematical Association]] for 1959.{{r|pres}}
==Life== Adams earned a degree from [[Bedford College, London]], with second-class honours in mathematics in 1911.{{r|obit|ulhr}} Her work as an inspector was centred on the [[West Country]] and particularly [[Bristol]].{{r|obit}}
She joined the [[Mathematical Association]] in approximately 1915,{{r|obit}} and became a member of the Teaching Sub-Committee of the Mathematical Association in 1946.{{r|melrose}} When she became president of the Mathematical Association in 1959, she became only the second woman to hold that office since the association's founding in 1871, after [[Mary Cartwright]] in 1951,{{r|pres|obit}} and the second HMI, after W. C. Fletcher in 1939.{{r|pres|rollett}}
She died in 1966.{{r|obit}}
==Contributions== Adams had "considerable experience as a teacher and inspector" and wrote her book, ''A Background to Primary School Mathematics'' (1953), on the basis of that experience.{{r|edres}} It was aimed at teachers of primary-school mathematics, and used case studies from approximately 80 students to advocate linking the teaching of mathematics to the individual experiences of the students.{{r|cook}} Her book "inspired many teachers" and prefigured a greater emphasis on play with mathematical tools over rote learning.{{r|breakell}}
As a member of the Teaching Sub-Committee of the Mathematical Association, Adams helped shift the association's focus "from teaching to learning"{{r|breakell}} and from what should be taught to how it should be taught.{{r|obit}} Both her book and her presidential address to the Mathematical Association were a major impetus to the reform of mathematical education in the UK.{{r|breakell}}
